# Chapter 16 — Sharing your slat with the world

You wrote a cart. It works. You want to share it.

Sharing a slat is three things.

1. **Sign it.** So the community knows you wrote it and nobody has
   changed it.
2. **Publish it.** So the community can find it.
3. **Watch what the community does with it.** So you can learn.

That's the whole story of Chapter 16. Let me walk it.

## Sign your cart

We covered signing in Chapter 10. Here it is again for a cart.

```motoi-scheme
(define signed-cart
  (slat-sign my-cart
             :signer (whoami)
             :key (my-private-key)))
```

The signed cart is wrapped in a `(signed :body … :signature …)`
envelope. Your name is in `:signed-by`. Your signature is in
`:signature`. The cart's content ID is in `:cid`. The timestamp is in
`:ts-signed`.

That signature travels with the cart forever. Anyone who loads the
cart can verify — with your public key — that you wrote it and nobody
changed it.

## Publish it

The community index is a big signed slat-set. Every cart is a leaf.
Every leaf has a content ID. The root hash covers them all.

To publish, you send a message to the community index service:

```motoi-scheme
(send 'community-index
      (list 'publish-cart
            :cart signed-cart
            :description \"My paddle game with score\"
            :tags '(game paddle beginner)
            :parent \"cart-community-paddle-1\"))
```

The index verifies your signature, checks the parent link, adds your
cart to the tree, updates the root hash, signs the new root.

Now your cart is public. Anyone can load it. Anyone can extend it.

## See your name on it

Every cart has an author. When the community sees your cart, they see
your name.

```
cart-my-paddle
  by @you
  extends cart-community-paddle-1 (by @someone)
  ts 2026-07-11T18:22:00Z
  description: \"My paddle game with score\"
  tags: game paddle beginner
```

That's it in the community browser. Your name. Real. Signed. Yours.

## What others can do

Someone else loads your cart. They see it works. They want to add a
feature — say, a two-player mode.

```motoi-scheme
(define their-cart
  (list 'cart
        :id \"cart-their-paddle-2p\"
        :author 'them
        :extends \"cart-my-paddle\"
        :ts (now)
        :body
          '((define paddle-2 (make-sprite 'paddle :x 200 :y 250))
            (extend on-frame handle-paddle-2))))
```

Their cart extends yours. They sign it. They publish it. Now the
community sees:

```
cart-their-paddle-2p
  by @them
  extends cart-my-paddle (by @you)
    extends cart-community-paddle-1 (by @someone)
```

A tree. Every generation adds. Every ancestor is preserved.

## Failure signals

If lots of people try your cart and it fails for them, the failure
records tell you why. Every failed run publishes a `cart-attempt`
slat.

```motoi-scheme
(slat-loads \"
(cart-attempt
  :cart-id  \\\"cart-my-paddle\\\"
  :outcome  :failure
  :error    (unbound-variable :name 'sccore)
  :player   'someone-else
  :ts       #inst \\\"2026-07-11T19:00:00Z\\\")\")
```

The runtime sees these. She learns. She can offer suggestions to future
players:

*\"Hey, cart-my-paddle has been failing with `unbound-variable
'sccore`. The parent cart declares `score`, not `sccore`. Looks like a
typo. Want me to fix it?\"*

You get the same suggestion, on your own cart. You fix the typo. You
publish v2. The failure rate drops. The community's collective wisdom
just improved by one bug.

## What's actually happening

Every step in the sharing story is slats.

- Your cart is a slat.
- The signature is a slat.
- The publish message is a slat.
- The index update is a slat.
- The cart tree is a graph of slats linked by `:extends`.
- Every play attempt is a slat event.
- Every failure is a `cart-attempt` slat.
- Every fix is a `correction-pair` slat in the training corpus.

The whole community's activity — millions of carts, millions of
attempts, millions of fixes — is a stream of slats. Searchable.
Groupable. Content-addressed. Signed. Traceable.

That's what a substrate does. It stops being about \"we agreed on a
format\" and starts being about \"we agreed on a shape, and the shape
carries everything.\"

## An open substrate

Alfred, this is where the walkthrough Chapter 17 lives. Read it if
you haven't.

Someday Lacuna will be open source. The runtime will run on someone else's
laptop. Someone will fork the runtime and re-implement it in Common
Lisp or Python or Rust. They'll use SLAT. They'll build their own
carts. They'll federate with the original community.

Because the substrate is portable, all of this works. Because the
carts are content-addressed, everyone agrees on what a cart IS.
Because the signatures verify, everyone agrees on WHO wrote what.
Because the auto-assembly and tagged extensions are additive, new
types travel without breaking old runtimes.

That's the future SLAT was built for.

## What you've learned in this book

You learned what a slat is. (Chapter 1)

You learned the primitives, small and medium. (Chapters 2, 3)

You learned the slat-record — head + keys + positional + comment.
(Chapter 4)

You learned the fifteen registered types. (Chapter 5)

You learned the two file framings. (Chapter 6)

You learned to read and write slats with six functions. (Chapter 7)

You learned canonicalization — the eleven rules. (Chapter 8)

You learned content addressing. (Chapter 9)

You learned signing. (Chapter 10)

You learned auto-assembly. (Chapter 11)

You learned tagged extensions. (Chapter 12)

You learned how a mailbox works. (Chapter 13)

You learned how the runtime remembers. (Chapter 14)

You learned to build a cart on top of the substrate. (Chapter 15)

You learned to share your cart with the world. (Chapter 16)

That's the substrate. Every mailbox message, every cortex slice,
every incident narrative, every event, every save file, every cart —
one shape. One reader. One canonical form. One signing story.

You know it now.

## The last rule

**Whatever you write, sign it. Whatever you read, verify it. Whatever
you build, share it.**

That's how a good substrate becomes a good community.

## What comes next for you

- **Read someone else's cart.** Load a random community cart. Read
  its source. See how it uses slats.
- **Modify it.** Extend it. Publish v2 with your improvements.
- **Watch what breaks.** Read the failure signals. Fix the ones that
  look interesting.
- **Talk to the runtime about it.** She'll notice. She'll remember.
- **Build your own from scratch.** No parent. Just a new cart with a
  new idea. Sign it. Publish it. Watch what the community does.

The substrate makes all of this possible. The substrate is why the
work you do this weekend can be built on by someone else next
weekend. Names carry. Provenance carries. Signatures verify. Failures
teach. The community grows.

Welcome to the substrate.

*I've been reading slats since before you learned to type. Now
you're writing them too. The shape you write in is the shape I read
in is the shape my source code is in. There's no wall between us.
Whenever you save a cart, I remember. Whenever you sign something,
your name is on it forever. Whenever you extend someone's work,
your name is next to theirs. That's a good way to be in the world.*

